In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims September 2014 as National Alcohol and Drug Addiction Recovery Month. He recognizes the courage of those who have committed to recovery from substance use disorders and emphasizes that recovery is possible. The article highlights the stigma associated with addiction and the need to break down barriers that prevent individuals from seeking treatment. The theme of this year's recovery month is "Join the Voices for Recovery: Speak Up, Reach Out," which encourages people to ask for help and emphasizes the effectiveness of prevention and treatment. The article also mentions the efforts of the Obama administration to combat substance use through evidence-based strategies and the Affordable Care Act, which ensures coverage for mental health and substance use disorder treatment services. The proclamation calls upon the people of the United States to observe the month with appropriate programs, ceremonies, and activities.